This dialog is used to define general settings when working with %PRODUCTNAME. Enter your personal data, the defaults to be used when saving documents, and paths to important files. These settings will be saved automatically and used in later sessions as well.
target: %PRODUCTNAME  аус адуларазы араҟа азеиԥш рхиарақәа реиқәыршәара алшоит.  Уи анаҩысангьы, адиалог аҿы ахархәаҩ идыррақәа арбазар ҟалоит, иара убас аиқәырхареи акьыԥхьреи рырхиагақәеи, акрызҵазкуа афаилқәа рахь амҩеи. Арҭ архиарақәа рхала еиқәхоит, анаҩыстәи аусура асеанс аан урҭ ҿыц рырхиара шәықәшәом.

source: This is where you make settings concerning language and writing aids for your work with %PRODUCTNAME.
target: Араҟа %PRODUCTNAME аус адулараан абызшәақәа рҷыдарақәа ирықәыршәаны архиагақәа реиқәыршәара ауеит.

source: This is where you configure %PRODUCTNAME for the Internet. You can define search engines or save your proxy settings.
target: Араҟа %PRODUCTNAME азеиԥш ахиарақәа аурбар ҟалоит аинтернет аҿы аусуразы, хаҭала аԥошьҭа асервер, аԥшаага машьынақәа, иара убас прокси архиарақәа

source: This is where you specify various settings for text documents. These settings determine how your text documents are handled in %PRODUCTNAME and are valid for all new %PRODUCTNAME Writer documents. You can also define a few settings for the active text document if you save it afterwards.
target: Араҟа атексттә документқәа рзы шьақәзыргыло еиуеиԥшым архиагақәа ашәырбар алшоит, %PRODUCTNAME урҭ аус шаднауло шьақәзыргыло. Арҭ архиагақәа иҿыцу адокументқәа %PRODUCTNAME Writer аҿы ахархәара роуеит. Шәара ишәылшоит иара убас изаамҭанытәу атекст документ азы хышәарақәак рзалхра, урҭ наҟ-наҟ адокумент анеикәшәырхо иацаанхарц.

source: This is where you define the basic settings for %PRODUCTNAME documents in HTML format. For example, you decide which contents should be displayed on the screen or printed, how the pages are scrolled on the screen, in which color keywords are highlighted in the source text and much more.
target: Араҟа адокументқәа %PRODUCTNAME аформат HTML аҿы иҟоу рзы  ихадоу абарҭ реиԥш иҟоу архиагақәа шәыԥшаар алшоит: адыррақәа ралхра аекран ахь мамзаргьы акьыԥхьрахь рцәыргаразы,  ашьшьыҳәа адаҟьақәа аекран аҿы реиҭагара, ихадоу ажәақәа рыԥштәы убас иҵегьы

source: This is where you define various global settings for spreadsheets. For example, you can define which contents should be displayed and in which direction the cursor will move after you enter data in a cell. You also define sort lists, the number of the decimal places displayed, etc.
target: Араҟа иҟауҵар ҟалоит аелектронтә таблицазы аглобалтә ҳәа изышьҭоу архиагақәа.  Шәара ишәылшоит, иаҳҳәап, иазгәашәҭар иарбан гәылаҵоу иарбатәу, иара убасгьы ахырхага аиҭаҵра ахырхарҭа, арбагақәа аблаҭа  ианҭажәгало. Шәара ишәылшоит ахьӡынҵа аилырхреи аизцәаҳәақәа рзеиԥш хыԥхьаӡареи рарбара.

source: This is where you define the settings that apply to all newly saved presentations. Among other things, you decide which contents are displayed on the slides, which default unit of measure is used, if and how grid alignment is used, and if notes and handouts are always printed.
target: Араҟа иалыршахоит  аӡыргаразы иаԥҵахо адокументқәа рзы архиагақәа реиҿкаара. Шәара ишәылшоит иашәырбар, иаҳҳәап, иарбан рбагақәоу адаҟьақәа рҿы ижәбарц ишәҭаху, ииашоу ашага ак ашьақәыргылара, акаҭала адокумент ариашашьа, иара убас иалышәхыр шәылшоит ишәҭахума еснагь азгәаҭақәеи атезисқәеи ркьыԥхьра.

source: This is where you define the settings for drawing documents. Among other things, you determine which contents are displayed on the pages, which scale is used, if and how grid alignment is used, and which contents are printed by default.
target: Араҟа иҟауҵар ҟалоит еиуеиԥшым аглобалтә рхиагақәа асахьақәа рдокументқәа рзы. Иаҳҳәап, иарбан дыррақәоу адаҟьақәа рҿы иаарԥшлатәу, азеиԥш масштаб, каҭала ариашашьа, иара убас иагәылоу  ишыҟоу еиԥш акьыԥхьра.

source: This is where you select the print format and print options for all newly saved formula documents. These options take effect when you want to print a formula directly from %PRODUCTNAME Math.
target: Араҟа иалхзар ауеит акьыԥхь азы аформати ахышәарақәеи ҿыц еиқәырхахо адокуметқәа зегьы раҳасабқәҵага. Арҭ ахышәарақәа азԥхьагәаҭоуп аҳасабқәҵага ишиашоу %PRODUCTNAME Math аҟынтәи икьыԥхьтәызар.

source: Editing a Report Created by the Report Wizard

When you receive a signed document, and the software reports that the signature is valid, this does not mean that you can be absolutely sure that the document is the same that the sender has sent. Signing documents with software certificates is not a perfectly secure method. Numerous ways are possible to circumvent the security features.
target: When you receive a signed document, and the software reports that the signature is valid, this does not mean that you can be absolutely sure that the document is the same that the sender has sent. Signing documents with software certificates is not a perfectly secure method. Numerous ways are possible to circumvent the security features.

source: Example: Think about someone wants to camouflage his identity to be a sender from your bank. He can easily get a certificate using a false name, then send you any signed e-mail pretending he is working for your bank. You will get that e-mail, and the e-mail or the document within has the "valid signed" icon.
target: Example: Think about someone wants to camouflage his identity to be a sender from your bank. He can easily get a certificate using a false name, then send you any signed e-mail pretending he is working for your bank. You will get that e-mail, and the e-mail or the document within has the "valid signed" icon.

source: The validation of a signature is not a legally binding assurement of any kind.
target: The validation of a signature is not a legally binding assurement of any kind.

source: On Windows operating systems, the Windows features of validating a signature are used. On Solaris and Linux systems, files that are supplied by Thunderbird, Mozilla or Firefox are used. You must ensure that the files that are in use within your system are really the original files that were supplied by the original developers. For malevolent intruders, there are numerous ways to replace original files with other files that they supply.
target: On Windows operating systems, the Windows features of validating a signature are used. On Solaris and Linux systems, files that are supplied by Thunderbird, Mozilla or Firefox are used. You must ensure that the files that are in use within your system are really the original files that were supplied by the original developers. For malevolent intruders, there are numerous ways to replace original files with other files that they supply.

source: The messages about validation of a signature that you see in %PRODUCTNAME are the messages that the validation files return. The %PRODUCTNAME software has no way to ensure that the messages reflect the true status of any certificate. The %PRODUCTNAME software only displays the messages that other files that are not under control of %PRODUCTNAME report. There is no legal responsibility of %PRODUCTNAME that the displayed messages reflect the true status of a digital signature.

source: Open the database file that contains the database table to be exported. Click Tables to view the tables, or click Queries to view the queries.
target: Open the database file that contains the database table to be exported. Click Tables to view the tables, or click Queries to view the queries.

target: In the Base window, right-click the name of the table to export. Choose <emph>Copy</emph> from the context menu.

source: Click cell A1 in the new Calc window, then choose <emph>Edit - Paste</emph>.
target: Click cell A1 in the new Calc window, then choose <emph>Edit - Paste</emph>.

source: Now you can save or export the data to many file types.
target: Now you can save or export the data to many file types.

source: You can import text files, spreadsheet files, and your system address book in read-only mode only.
target: You can import text files, spreadsheet files, and your system address book in read-only mode only.

source: When you import from a text or spreadsheet file, the file must have a first row of header information. The second row of the file is the first valid data row. The format of every field in the second row determines the format for the entire column. Any format information from a spreadsheet file gets lost when importing to Base.
target: When you import from a text or spreadsheet file, the file must have a first row of header information. The second row of the file is the first valid data row. The format of every field in the second row determines the format for the entire column. Any format information from a spreadsheet file gets lost when importing to Base.

source: For example, to ensure the first column has a text format, you must make sure that the first field of the first valid data row contains text. If a field in the first valid data row contains a number, the whole column is set to number format, and only numbers, no text, will be shown in that column.
target: For example, to ensure the first column has a text format, you must make sure that the first field of the first valid data row contains text. If a field in the first valid data row contains a number, the whole column is set to number format, and only numbers, no text, will be shown in that column.

source: With "Formulas" you will find all parts of the formulas.

source: With "Values" you will find the results of the calculations.
target: With "Values" you will find the results of the calculations.

source: Cell contents can be formatted in different ways. For example, a number can be formatted as a currency, to be displayed with a currency symbol. You see the currency symbol in the cell, but you cannot search for it.
target: Cell contents can be formatted in different ways. For example, a number can be formatted as a currency, to be displayed with a currency symbol. You see the currency symbol in the cell, but you cannot search for it.

target: Enter the text to find in the <emph>Search for</emph> text box.

source: When you click <emph>Find</emph>, Calc will select the next cell that contains your text. You can watch and edit the text, then click <emph>Find</emph> again to advance to the next found cell.
target: When you click <emph>Find</emph>, Calc will select the next cell that contains your text. You can watch and edit the text, then click <emph>Find</emph> again to advance to the next found cell.

target: If you closed the dialog, you can press a key combination (Ctrl+Shift+F) to find the next cell without opening the dialog.

source: By default, Calc searches the current sheet. Click <emph>More Options</emph>, then enable <emph>Search in all sheets</emph> to search through all sheets of the document.
target: By default, Calc searches the current sheet. Click <emph>More Options</emph>, then enable <emph>Search in all sheets</emph> to search through all sheets of the document.

source: When you click <emph>Find All</emph>, Calc selects all cells that contain your entry. Now you can for example set all found cells to bold, or apply a Cell Style to all at once.
target: When you click <emph>Find All</emph>, Calc selects all cells that contain your entry. Now you can for example set all found cells to bold, or apply a Cell Style to all at once.

target: On the first page of the <link href="text/schart/01/wiz_chart_type.xhp">Chart Wizard</link> you can choose a chart type.

source: An area chart shows values as points on the y axis. The x axis shows categories. The y values of each data series are connected by a line. The area between each two lines is filled with a color. The area chart's focus is to emphasize the changes from one category to the next.
target: An area chart shows values as points on the y axis. The x axis shows categories. The y values of each data series are connected by a line. The area between each two lines is filled with a color. The area chart's focus is to emphasize the changes from one category to the next.

source: Normal - this subtype plots all values as absolute y values. It first plots the area of the last column in the data range, then the next to last, and so on, and finally the first column of data is drawn. Thus, if the values in the first column are higher than other values, the last drawn area will hide the other areas.
target: Normal - this subtype plots all values as absolute y values. It first plots the area of the last column in the data range, then the next to last, and so on, and finally the first column of data is drawn. Thus, if the values in the first column are higher than other values, the last drawn area will hide the other areas.

source: Stacked - this subtypes plots values cumulative stacked on each other. It ensures that all values are visible, and no data set is hidden by others. However, the y values no longer represent absolute values, except for the last column which is drawn at the bottom of the stacked areas.
target: Stacked - this subtypes plots values cumulative stacked on each other. It ensures that all values are visible, and no data set is hidden by others. However, the y values no longer represent absolute values, except for the last column which is drawn at the bottom of the stacked areas.

source: Percent - this subtype plots values cumulative stacked on each other and scaled as percentage of the category total.
target: Percent - this subtype plots values cumulative stacked on each other and scaled as percentage of the category total.

source: Choose from the following chart types, depending on data type and intended presentation effect.
target: Choose from the following chart types, depending on data type and intended presentation effect.

target: A line chart shows values as points on the y axis. The x axis shows categories. The y values of each data series can be connected by a line.

source: Points only - this subtype plots only points.
target: Points only - this subtype plots only points.

source: Points and lines - this subtype plots points and connects points of the same data series by a line.
target: Points and lines - this subtype plots points and connects points of the same data series by a line.

source: Lines only - this subtype plots only lines.
target: Lines only - this subtype plots only lines.

source: 3D lines - this subtype connects points of the same data series by a 3D line.
target: 3D lines - this subtype connects points of the same data series by a 3D line.

source: Mark <emph>Stack series</emph> to arrange the points' y values cumulative above each other. The y values no longer represent absolute values, except for the first column which is drawn at the bottom of the stacked points. If you select <emph>Percent</emph>, the y values are scaled as percentage of the category total.
target: Mark <emph>Stack series</emph> to arrange the points' y values cumulative above each other. The y values no longer represent absolute values, except for the first column which is drawn at the bottom of the stacked points. If you select <emph>Percent</emph>, the y values are scaled as percentage of the category total.

source: Mark <emph>Smooth lines</emph> to draw curves through the points instead of straight lines. Click <emph>Properties</emph> for a <link href="text/schart/01/smooth_line_properties.xhp">dialog</link> to change the curves' properties.
target: Mark <emph>Smooth lines</emph> to draw curves through the points instead of straight lines. Click <emph>Properties</emph> for a <link href="text/schart/01/smooth_line_properties.xhp">dialog</link> to change the curves' properties.

source: This type shows a bar chart or bar graph with vertical bars. The height of each bar is proportional to its value. The x axis shows categories. The y axis shows the value for each category.
target: This type shows a bar chart or bar graph with vertical bars. The height of each bar is proportional to its value. The x axis shows categories. The y axis shows the value for each category.

source: Normal - this subtype shows all data values belonging to a category next to each other. Main focus is on the individual absolute values, compared to every other value.
target: Normal - this subtype shows all data values belonging to a category next to each other. Main focus is on the individual absolute values, compared to every other value.

source: Stacked - this subtype shows the data values of each category on top of each other. Main focus is the overall category value and the individual contribution of each value within its category.
target: Stacked - this subtype shows the data values of each category on top of each other. Main focus is the overall category value and the individual contribution of each value within its category.

source: Percent - this subtype shows the relative percentage of each data value with regard to the total of its category. Main focus is the relative contribution of each value to the category's total.
target: Percent - this subtype shows the relative percentage of each data value with regard to the total of its category. Main focus is the relative contribution of each value to the category's total.

target: You can enable a <link href="text/schart/01/three_d_view.xhp">3D view</link> of the data values. The "realistic" scheme tries to give the best 3D look. The "simple" scheme tries to mimic the chart view of other Office products.

target: For 3D charts, you can select the shape of each data value from Box, Cylinder, Cone, and Pyramid.

source: This type shows a bar chart or bar graph with horizontal bars. The length of each bar is proportional to its value. The y axis shows categories. The x axis shows the value for each category.
target: This type shows a bar chart or bar graph with horizontal bars. The length of each bar is proportional to its value. The y axis shows categories. The x axis shows the value for each category.

target: The open, low, high, and closing values of a row build together one data unit in the chart. A stock price data series consists of several rows containing such data units. The column containing the transaction volume builds an optional second data series.

target: Choose the <emph>Stock</emph> chart type on the first page of the <link href="text/schart/01/wiz_chart_type.xhp">Chart wizard</link>. Then select one of the four variants.

source: Based on<emph> low</emph><emph>and high </emph>column the Type 1 shows the distance between bottom price (low) and top price (high) by a vertical line.
target: Based on<emph> low</emph><emph>and high </emph>column the Type 1 shows the distance between bottom price (low) and top price (high) by a vertical line.

Type 2 draws the vertical line between the bottom and top price and adds a rectangle in front, which visualizes the range between the opening and closing price. %PRODUCTNAME uses different fill colors for raising values (the opening price is lower than the closing price) and falling values.
target: Based on <emph>open, low, high</emph>, and <emph>close</emph> column Type 2 generates the traditional "candle stick" chart. source: Based on <emph>volume, low, high</emph>, and <emph>close</emph> column chart Type 3 draws a chart like Type 1, with additional bars for the transaction volume.
target: Based on <emph>volume, low, high</emph>, and <emph>close</emph> column chart Type 3 draws a chart like Type 1, with additional bars for the transaction volume.

source: Based on all five data columns <emph>volume, open, low, high</emph>, and <emph>close</emph>, Type 4 combines a chart of Type 2 with a bar chart for the transaction volume.
target: Based on all five data columns <emph>volume, open, low, high</emph>, and <emph>close</emph>, Type 4 combines a chart of Type 2 with a bar chart for the transaction volume.

source: A pie chart shows values as circular sectors of the total circle. The length of the arc, or the area of each sector, is proportional to its value.
target: A pie chart shows values as circular sectors of the total circle. The length of the arc, or the area of each sector, is proportional to its value.

source: Pie - this subtype shows sectors as colored areas of the total pie, for one data column only. In the created chart, you can click and drag any sector to separate that sector from the remaining pie or to join it back.
target: Pie - this subtype shows sectors as colored areas of the total pie, for one data column only. In the created chart, you can click and drag any sector to separate that sector from the remaining pie or to join it back.

source: Exploded pie - this subtype shows the sectors already separated from each other. In the created chart, you can click and drag any sector to move it along a radial from the pie's center.
target: Exploded pie - this subtype shows the sectors already separated from each other. In the created chart, you can click and drag any sector to move it along a radial from the pie's center.

source: Donut - this subtype can show multiple data columns. Each data column is shown as one donut shape with a hole inside, where the next data column can be shown. In the created chart, you can click and drag an outer sector to move it along a radial from the donut's center.

source: An XY chart in its basic form is based on one data series consisting of a name, a list of x‑values, and a list of y‑values. Each value pair (x|y) is shown as a point in a coordinate system. The name of the data series is associated with the y‑values and shown in the legend.
target: An XY chart in its basic form is based on one data series consisting of a name, a list of x‑values, and a list of y‑values. Each value pair (x|y) is shown as a point in a coordinate system. The name of the data series is associated with the y‑values and shown in the legend.

target: draw the graph of a function

target: explore the statistical association of quantitative variables

target: You can choose an XY chart variant on the first page of the <link href="text/schart/01/wiz_chart_type.xhp">Chart Wizard</link>, or by choosing <item type="menuitem">Format - Chart Type </item>for a chart in edit mode.

source: The chart is created with default settings. After the chart is finished, you can edit its properties to change the appearance. Line styles and icons can be changed on the Line tab page of the data series properties dialog.
target: The chart is created with default settings. After the chart is finished, you can edit its properties to change the appearance. Line styles and icons can be changed on the Line tab page of the data series properties dialog.

source: Double-click any data point to open the <item type="menuitem">Data Series</item> dialog. Here you can click the Statistics tab and enable the display of statistical values. Some available values are mean value, variance, standard deviation, percentage, error margins, and regression curves or trend lines.
target: Double-click any data point to open the <item type="menuitem">Data Series</item> dialog. Here you can click the Statistics tab and enable the display of statistical values. Some available values are mean value, variance, standard deviation, percentage, error margins, and regression curves or trend lines.

source: Each data point is shown by an icon. %PRODUCTNAME uses default icons with different forms and colors for each data series. The default colors are set in Tools - Options - Charts - Default Colors.
target: Each data point is shown by an icon. %PRODUCTNAME uses default icons with different forms and colors for each data series. The default colors are set in Tools - Options - Charts - Default Colors.

source: This variant draws straight lines from one data point to the next. The data points are not shown by icons.
target: This variant draws straight lines from one data point to the next. The data points are not shown by icons.

source: The drawing order is the same as the order in the data series. Mark <emph>Sort by X Values</emph> to draw the lines in the order of the x values. This sorting applies only to the chart, not to the data in the table.
target: The drawing order is the same as the order in the data series. Mark <emph>Sort by X Values</emph> to draw the lines in the order of the x values. This sorting applies only to the chart, not to the data in the table.

source: This variant shows points and lines at the same time.
target: This variant shows points and lines at the same time.

source: The lines are shown like tapes. The data points are not shown by icons. In the finished chart choose <link href="text/schart/01/three_d_view.xhp">3D View</link> to set properties like illumination and angle of view.
target: The lines are shown like tapes. The data points are not shown by icons. In the finished chart choose <link href="text/schart/01/three_d_view.xhp">3D View</link> to set properties like illumination and angle of view.

source: Mark Smooth Lines to draw curves instead of straight line segments. The x values must be sorted. Therefore you cannot smooth parameter curves like spirals.
target: Mark Smooth Lines to draw curves instead of straight line segments. The x values must be sorted. Therefore you cannot smooth parameter curves like spirals.

source: Click Properties to set details for the curves.
target: Click Properties to set details for the curves.

source: <emph>Cubic Spline</emph> interpolates your data points with polynomials of degree 3. The transitions between the polynomial pieces are smooth, having the same slope and curvature.
target: <emph>Cubic Spline</emph> interpolates your data points with polynomials of degree 3. The transitions between the polynomial pieces are smooth, having the same slope and curvature.

source: The Resolution determines how many line segments are calculated to draw a piece of polynomial between two data points. You can see the intermediate points if you click any data point.
target: The Resolution determines how many line segments are calculated to draw a piece of polynomial between two data points. You can see the intermediate points if you click any data point.

source: <emph>B-Spline</emph> uses the data points as control points to form a B-spline curve. Those curves are built piecewise from polynomials. The <emph>Data points order</emph> sets the degree k of these polynomials.
target: <emph>B-Spline</emph> uses the data points as control points to form a B-spline curve. Those curves are built piecewise from polynomials. The <emph>Data points order</emph> sets the degree k of these polynomials.

source: You see layouts of one to six slides per page. Those preview icons only show the number of slides on a page, but not their shape and position.
target: You see layouts of one to six slides per page. Those preview icons only show the number of slides on a page, but not their shape and position.

source: Click the Layout preview icon with the number of slides that you want on every sheet of paper.
target: Click the Layout preview icon with the number of slides that you want on every sheet of paper.

source: Choose <emph>Insert - Page Number</emph> to open the <emph>Header and Footer</emph> dialog box.
target: Choose <emph>Insert - Page Number</emph> to open the <emph>Header and Footer</emph> dialog box.

source: Click <emph>Notes and Handouts</emph> to enter the header and footer text for handouts.
target: Click <emph>Notes and Handouts</emph> to enter the header and footer text for handouts.

source: You see four areas on this dialog with check boxes for Header, Date and time, Footer, and Page number. These four areas correspond to the four areas in the corners of the handout master view.
target: You see four areas on this dialog with check boxes for Header, Date and time, Footer, and Page number. These four areas correspond to the four areas in the corners of the handout master view.

source: Enter text for header, footer, and date. Check the <emph>Page number</emph> box, if you want to number the handout pages. Ensure the <emph>Header</emph> check box is enabled if you want your header text to be printed.
target: Enter text for header, footer, and date. Check the <emph>Page number</emph> box, if you want to number the handout pages. Ensure the <emph>Header</emph> check box is enabled if you want your header text to be printed.

source: The fields in the handout master view on screen are not updated, but the text that you entered will be printed.
target: The fields in the handout master view on screen are not updated, but the text that you entered will be printed.

source: Select <emph>Handouts</emph> or <emph>Notes</emph> and click OK on both dialogs.
target: Выберите <emph>Раздаточные материалы</emph> и нажмите кнопку "OK" в обоих диалоговых окнах.

source: If you want another layout of the slides on the printed paper pages, use the mouse to move the slides around on the Handout view.

source: Different ways exist to start a slide show. Once a slide show is running, you can take control pressing keys or clicking the mouse buttons.
target: Different ways exist to start a slide show. Once a slide show is running, you can take control pressing keys or clicking the mouse buttons.

source: By default, a slide show always starts with the first slide. You advance manually through slides up to the last slide. You can change these settings.
target: By default, a slide show always starts with the first slide. You advance manually through slides up to the last slide. You can change these settings.

source: Choose <emph>Slide Show - Slide Show</emph> to run the show.
target: Choose <emph>Slide Show - Slide Show</emph> to run the show.

source: If you want all shows to start from the current slide instead of the first slide, choose <emph>Tools - Options - %PRODUCTNAME Impress - General</emph> and click <emph>Always with current page</emph>.
target: If you want all shows to start from the current slide instead of the first slide, choose <emph>Tools - Options - %PRODUCTNAME Impress - General</emph> and click <emph>Always with current page</emph>.

source: Click to advance to the next effect or to the next slide.
target: Click to advance to the next effect or to the next slide.

source: Press <item type="keycode">Esc</item> to abort the show before the end.
target: Press <item type="keycode">Esc</item> to abort the show before the end.

source: Many more keys are available to <link href="text/simpress/04/01020000.xhp">control a slide show</link>. You can also right-click to open a context menu with useful commands.
target: Many more keys are available to <link href="text/simpress/04/01020000.xhp">control a slide show</link>. You can also right-click to open a context menu with useful commands.

target: Showing an automatic slide show (kiosk mode)

target: For an automatic change to the next slide, you must assign a slide transition to each slide.

target: On the Task Pane, click <emph>Slide Transition</emph> to open that tab page.

target: In the <emph>Advance slide</emph> area, click <emph>Automatically after</emph>, and select a time duration.

source: You can assign a different time for every slide to advance to the next slide. The <link href="text/simpress/guide/rehearse_timings.xhp">rehearse timings</link> feature can assist you to get the timing right.
target: You can assign a different time for every slide to advance to the next slide. The <link href="text/simpress/guide/rehearse_timings.xhp">rehearse timings</link> feature can assist you to get the timing right.

source: To advance to the first slide, after all slides have been shown, you must set the slide show to repeat automatically.
target: To advance to the first slide, after all slides have been shown, you must set the slide show to repeat automatically.

source: In the Type area, click <emph>Auto</emph> and select a pause time between shows.
target: In the Type area, click <emph>Auto</emph> and select a pause time between shows.

target: When you create a new slide show using the <link href="text/shared/autopi/01050000.xhp">Presentation Wizard</link>, you can select the duration of slides and of the pause, on the third wizard page.

source: In text documents you can find words, formatting, styles, and more. You can navigate from one result to the next, or you can highlight all results at once, then apply another format or replace the words by other text.
target: In text documents you can find words, formatting, styles, and more. You can navigate from one result to the next, or you can highlight all results at once, then apply another format or replace the words by other text.

source: To find text within the whole document, open the Find & Replace dialog without any active text selection. If you want to search only a part of your document, first select that part of text, then open the Find & Replace dialog.
target: To find text within the whole document, open the Find  Replace dialog without any active text selection. If you want to search only a part of your document, first select that part of text, then open the Find  Replace dialog.

source: When you click <emph>Find</emph>, Writer will show you the next text that is equal to your entry. You can watch and edit the text, then click <emph>Find</emph> again to advance to the next found text.
target: When you click <emph>Find</emph>, Writer will show you the next text that is equal to your entry. You can watch and edit the text, then click <emph>Find</emph> again to advance to the next found text.

source: If you closed the dialog, you can press a key combination (Ctrl+Shift+F) to find the next text without opening the dialog.
target: If you closed the dialog, you can press a key combination (Ctrl+Shift+F) to find the next text without opening the dialog.

source: Alternatively, you can use the icons at the lower right of the document to navigate to the next text or to any other object in the document.
target: Alternatively, you can use the icons at the lower right of the document to navigate to the next text or to any other object in the document.

source: When you click <emph>Find All</emph>, Writer selects all text that is equal to your entry. Now you can for example set all found text to bold, or apply a Character Style to all at once.
target: When you click <emph>Find All</emph>, Writer selects all text that is equal to your entry. Now you can for example set all found text to bold, or apply a Character Style to all at once.

source: Unlike searching text, replacing text cannot be restricted to the current selection only.
target: Unlike searching text, replacing text cannot be restricted to the current selection only.

source: Choose Edit - Find & Replace to open the Find & Replace dialog.
target: Choose Edit - Find & Replace to open the Find & Replace dialog.

source: Enter the text to search in the <emph>Search for </emph>text box.
target: Enter the text to search in the <emph>Search for </emph>text box.

source: Enter the text to replace the found text in the <emph>Replace with</emph> text box.
target: Enter the text to replace the found text in the <emph>Replace with</emph> text box.

source: When you click <emph>Replace</emph>, Writer will search the whole document for the text in the <emph>Search for</emph> box, starting at the current cursor position. When text is found, Writer highlights the text and waits for your response. Click <emph>Replace</emph> to replace the highlighted text in the document with the text in the <emph>Replace with</emph> text box. Click <emph>Find</emph> to advance to the next found text without replacing the current selection.
target: When you click <emph>Replace</emph>, Writer will search the whole document for the text in the <emph>Search for</emph> box, starting at the current cursor position. When text is found, Writer highlights the text and waits for your response. Click <emph>Replace</emph> to replace the highlighted text in the document with the text in the <emph>Replace with</emph> text box. Click <emph>Find</emph> to advance to the next found text without replacing the current selection.

source: When you click <emph>Replace All</emph>, Writer replaces all text that matches your entry.
target: When you click <emph>Replace All</emph>, Writer replaces all text that matches your entry.

source: You want to find all text in your document to which a certain Paragraph Style is assigned, for example the "Heading 2" style.
target: You want to find all text in your document to which a certain Paragraph Style is assigned, for example the "Heading 2" style.

source: The <emph>Search for</emph> text box now is a list box, where you can select any of the Paragraph Styles that are applied in the current document.
target: The <emph>Search for</emph> text box now is a list box, where you can select any of the Paragraph Styles that are applied in the current document.

source: Select the style to search for, then click <emph>Find</emph> or <emph>Find All</emph>.
target: Select the style to search for, then click <emph>Find</emph> or <emph>Find All</emph>.

source: You want to find all text in your document to which a certain direct character formatting is assigned.
target: You want to find all text in your document to which a certain direct character formatting is assigned.

source: Finding formats only finds direct character attributes, it does not find attributes applied as part of a style.
target: Finding formats only finds direct character attributes, it does not find attributes applied as part of a style.

source: The similarity search can find text that is almost the same as your search text. You can set the number of characters that are allowed to differ.
target: The similarity search can find text that is almost the same as your search text. You can set the number of characters that are allowed to differ.

source: Check the <emph>Similarity search</emph> option and optionally click the <emph>...</emph> button to change the settings. (Setting all three numbers to 1 works fine for english text.)
target: Check the <emph>Similarity search</emph> option and optionally click the <emph>...</emph> button to change the settings. (Setting all three numbers to 1 works fine for english text.)

source: When you have enabled asian language support under <emph>Tools - Options - Language Settings - Languages</emph>, the Find & Replace dialog offers options to search asian text.
target: When you have enabled asian language support under <emph>Tools - Options - Language Settings - Languages</emph>, the Find  Replace dialog offers options to search asian text.

source: The Navigator is the main tool for finding and selecting objects. You can also use the Navigator to move and arrange chapters, providing an outline view to your document.
target: The Navigator is the main tool for finding and selecting objects. You can also use the Navigator to move and arrange chapters, providing an outline view to your document.

source: Use the Navigator for inserting objects, links and references within the same document or from other open documents. See the <link href="text/swriter/guide/navigator.xhp">Navigator</link> guide for more information.
target: Use the Navigator for inserting objects, links and references within the same document or from other open documents. See the <link href="text/swriter/guide/navigator.xhp">Navigator</link> guide for more information.

source: Click the icon with the blue circle at the bottom right part of your document to open the small <emph>Navigation</emph> window.
target: Click the icon with the blue circle at the bottom right part of your document to open the small <emph>Navigation</emph> window.

source: In Writer, a page number is a field that you can insert into your text.
target: In Writer, a page number is a field that you can insert into your text.

source: Choose <emph>Insert - Fields - Page Number</emph> to insert a page number at the current cursor position.
target: Choose <emph>Insert - Fields - Page Number</emph> to insert a page number at the current cursor position.

source: If you see the text "Page number" instead of the number, choose <emph>View - Field names</emph>.
target: If you see the text "Page number" instead of the number, choose <emph>View - Field names</emph>.

source: However, these fields will change position when you add or remove text. So it is best to insert the page number field into a header or footer that has the same position and that is repeated on every page.
target: However, these fields will change position when you add or remove text. So it is best to insert the page number field into a header or footer that has the same position and that is repeated on every page.

source: Choose <emph>Insert - Header - (name of page style)</emph> or <emph>Insert - Footer - (name of page style)</emph> to add a header or footer to all pages with the current Page Style.
target: Choose <emph>Insert - Header - (name of page style)</emph> or <emph>Insert - Footer - (name of page style)</emph> to add a header or footer to all pages with the current Page Style.

source: Starting with a defined page number
target: Starting with a defined page number

source: Now you want some more control on page numbers. You are writing a text document that should start with page number 12.
target: Now you want some more control on page numbers. You are writing a text document that should start with page number 12.

source: Click into the first paragraph of your document.
target: Click into the first paragraph of your document.

source: In the Breaks area, enable <emph>Insert</emph>. Enable <emph>With Page Style</emph> just to be able to set the new <emph>Page number</emph>. Click <emph>OK</emph>.
target: In the Breaks area, enable <emph>Insert</emph>. Enable <emph>With Page Style</emph> just to be able to set the new <emph>Page number</emph>. Click <emph>OK</emph>.

source: The new page number is an attribute of the first paragraph of the page.
target: The new page number is an attribute of the first paragraph of the page.

source: You want roman page numbers running i, ii, iii, iv, and so on.
target: You want roman page numbers running i, ii, iii, iv, and so on.

source: Double-click directly before the page number field. You see the <emph>Edit Fields</emph> dialog.
target: Double-click directly before the page number field. You see the <emph>Edit Fields</emph> dialog.

source: Select a number format and click <emph>OK</emph>.
target: Select a number format and click <emph>OK</emph>.

source: You need some pages with the roman numbering style, followed by the remaining pages in another style.
target: You need some pages with the roman numbering style, followed by the remaining pages in another style.

source: In Writer, you will need different Page Styles. The first Page Style has a footer with a page number field formatted for roman numbers. The following Page Style has a footer with a page number field formatted in another look.
target: In Writer, you will need different Page Styles. The first Page Style has a footer with a page number field formatted for roman numbers. The following Page Style has a footer with a page number field formatted in another look.

source: Both Page Styles must be separated by a page break. In Writer, you can have automatic page breaks and manually inserted page breaks.
target: Both Page Styles must be separated by a page break. In Writer, you can have automatic page breaks and manually inserted page breaks.

source: An <emph>automatic page break</emph> appears at the end of a page when the Page Style has a different "next style".
target: An <emph>automatic page break</emph> appears at the end of a page when the Page Style has a different "next style".

source: For example, the "First Page" Page Style has "Default" as the next style. To see this, you may press F11 to open the <emph>Styles and Formatting</emph> window, click the <emph>Page Styles</emph> icon, right-click the First Page entry. Choose <emph>Modify</emph> from the context menu. On the Organizer tab, you can see the "next style".
target: For example, the "First Page" Page Style has "Default" as the next style. To see this, you may press F11 to open the <emph>Styles and Formatting</emph> window, click the <emph>Page Styles</emph> icon, right-click the First Page entry. Choose <emph>Modify</emph> from the context menu. On the Organizer tab, you can see the "next style".

source: A <emph>manually inserted page break</emph> can be applied without or with a change of page styles.
target: A <emph>manually inserted page break</emph> can be applied without or with a change of page styles.

source: If you just press <item type="keycode">Ctrl+Enter</item>, you apply a page break without a change of styles.
target: If you just press <item type="keycode">Ctrl+Enter</item>, you apply a page break without a change of styles.

source: If you choose <emph>Insert - Manual break</emph>, you can insert a page break without or with a change of style or with a change of page number.
target: If you choose <emph>Insert - Manual break</emph>, you can insert a page break without or with a change of style or with a change of page number.

source: It depends on your document what is best: to use a manually inserted page break between Page Styles, or to use an automatic change. If you just need one title page with a different style than the other pages, you can use the automatic method:
target: It depends on your document what is best: to use a manually inserted page break between Page Styles, or to use an automatic change. If you just need one title page with a different style than the other pages, you can use the automatic method:

target: To apply a different page style to the first page

source: Click into the first page of your document.
target: Click into the first page of your document.

source: In the <emph>Styles and Formatting</emph> window, click the <emph>Page Styles</emph> icon.
target: In the <emph>Styles and Formatting</emph> window, click the <emph>Page Styles</emph> icon.

source: Now your title page has the style "First Page", and the next pages automatically have the "Default" style.
target: Now your title page has the style "First Page", and the next pages automatically have the "Default" style.

source: You can now for example insert a footer for the "Default" Page Style only, or insert footers to both Page Styles, but with differently formatted page number fields.
target: You can now for example insert a footer for the "Default" Page Style only, or insert footers to both Page Styles, but with differently formatted page number fields.

source: To apply a manually inserted Page Style change
target: To apply a manually inserted Page Style change

source: Click at the start of the first paragraph on the page where a different Page Style will be applied.
target: Click at the start of the first paragraph on the page where a different Page Style will be applied.

source: Choose <emph>Insert - Manual Break</emph>. You see the <emph>Insert Break</emph> dialog.
target: Choose <emph>Insert - Manual Break</emph>. You see the <emph>Insert Break</emph> dialog.

source: In the Style list box, select a Page Style. You may set a new page number, too. Click <emph>OK</emph>.
target: In the Style list box, select a Page Style. You may set a new page number, too. Click <emph>OK</emph>.

target: Right-click a paragraph and choose Edit Paragraph Style - Indents  Spacing to change the indents for all paragraphs that have the same Paragraph Style.

source: Indents are calculated with respect to the left and right page margins. If you want the paragraph to extend into the page margin, enter a negative number.
target: Indents are calculated with respect to the left and right page margins. If you want the paragraph to extend into the page margin, enter a negative number.

source: The indents are different regarding the writing direction. For example, look at the "Before text" indent value in left-to-right languages. The left edge of the paragraph is indented with respect to the left page margin. In right-to-left languages, the right edge of the paragraph is indented with respect to the right page margin.
target: The indents are different regarding the writing direction. For example, look at the "Before text" indent value in left-to-right languages. source: For a hanging indent, enter a positive value for "Before text" and a negative value for "First line".

source: A master document master.odm consists of some text and links to the subdocuments sub1.odt and sub2.odt. In each subdocument a new paragraph style with the same name Style1 is defined and used, and the subdocuments are saved.
target: A master document master.odm consists of some text and links to the subdocuments sub1.odt and sub2.odt. In each subdocument a new paragraph style with the same name Style1 is defined and used, and the subdocuments are saved.

source: When you save the master document, the styles from the subdocuments are imported into the master document. First, the new style Style1 from the sub1.odt is imported. Next, the new styles from sub2.odt will be imported, but as Style1 now already is present in the master document, this style from sub2.odt will not be imported.
target: When you save the master document, the styles from the subdocuments are imported into the master document. First, the new style Style1 from the sub1.odt is imported. Next, the new styles from sub2.odt will be imported, but as Style1 now already is present in the master document, this style from sub2.odt will not be imported.

source: In the master document you now see the new style Style1 from the first subdocument. All Style1 paragraphs in the master document will be shown using the Style1 attributes from the first subdocument. However, the second subdocument by itself will not be changed. You see the Style1 paragraphs from the second subdocument with different attributes, depending whether you open the sub2.odt document by itself or as part of the master document.
target: In the master document you now see the new style Style1 from the first subdocument. All Style1 paragraphs in the master document will be shown using the Style1 attributes from the first subdocument. However, the second subdocument by itself will not be changed. You see the Style1 paragraphs from the second subdocument with different attributes, depending whether you open the sub2.odt document by itself or as part of the master document.

source: To avoid confusion, use the same document template for the master document and its subdocuments. This happens automatically when you create the master document and its subdocuments from an existing document with headings, using the command <emph>File - Send - Create Master Document</emph>.

source: User Defined Borders in Text Documents

source: When importing numbers from an HTML page, the decimal separator and the thousands separator characters differ according to the locale of the HTML page. The clipboard however contains no information about the locale. For example, the characters "1.000" copied from a German Web page most possibly mean "one thousand" because the period is the thousands separator in a German locale. If copied from an English Web page, the same characters stand for the number 1 as in "one dot zero zero zero".
target: When importing numbers from an HTML page, the decimal separator and the thousands separator characters differ according to the locale of the HTML page. The clipboard however contains no information about the locale. If copied from an English Web page, the same characters stand for the number 1 as in "one dot zero zero zero".
